license: MIT
abstract: >-
  Adaptive cancer therapy schedules drug-on/drug-off cycles based on biomarker
  dynamics, with the goal of preserving competitive pressure from drug-sensitive
  cells against drug-resistant ones. Three independent prior studies
  (Brady-Nicholls 2020, Strobl 2022, Gallagher 2025) fit different
  Lotka-Volterra parameterizations to overlapping clinical cohorts and converge
  on the empirical conclusion that approximately one effective parameter per
  patient is recoverable from PSA-only observation. We provide the structural
  explanation: the Fisher Information Matrix of the canonical 2-population
  multiplicative-death model has effective rank 1 of 4. The 3-population
  K-shift model used by Zhang 2017 has rank 3 of 6 with the unidentifiable
  subspace localized in the competition coefficients and drug-effectiveness
  parameter. The rank deficiency is schedule-invariant and channel-invariant:
  multi-modal observation channels improve precision but do not close the rank
  gap. We propagate this posterior structure through to clinical
  decision-making and show that on the real Bruchovsky 2008 IADT cohort (n=71)
  posterior-aware vs point-estimate optimal control disagrees for 37% of
  patients; on the Shaw 2007 cohort (n=15) the disagreement is 13%.
  Cohort-level hierarchical pooling recovers the rank-deficient directions:
  shrinkage of 86-87% on the most poorly-identified per-patient parameters,
  with cross-cohort agreement on population means to within 1-3%.
keywords:
  - adaptive cancer therapy
  - Lotka-Volterra
  - Fisher Information Matrix
  - identifiability
  - posterior-aware control
  - Bayesian decision theory
  - mCRPC
  - prostate cancer
